        <h3>What is health?</h3>
        <p>Health may be defined as a "complete/balanced condition" in which there is synchronisation between body and mind. Cells are the fundamental units of the body; cells with similar functions group together to form tissues like epithelial, connective, muscular, and nervous tissue. Different tissues together form organs, and organs form organ systems meant for physiological functions like circulation, respiration, and digestion. A living being — the "body" — is built from different levels of frameworks, from cells all the way up to organ systems, in order to perform complex functions.</p>

        <h3>The body's internal balance</h3>
        <p>Interactions within the different systems, and with the environment, lead to structural and functional "expressions" over time — a control mechanism that is still poorly understood. It is generally accepted that a "biological clock" within organisms controls timely events, though its exact location remains a mystery: whether it sits at the individual cellular level or somewhere higher. More complexly, the structural and functional expressions of these systems give rise to the "mind" — loaded with thoughts and actions for the expressions the "body" exhibits.</p>

        <h3>When balance breaks down</h3>
        <p>When the fine balance within the organ systems of the "body" is disturbed, it eventually disturbs the balance between "body" and "mind" — and the net result is individual diseases or syndromes.</p>
      </article>

